SENATE JOINT RESOLUTION 1203
By Johnson
A RESOLUTION to honor and congratulate Charles Edward
Bottens on the celebration of his 100th birthday.
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this General Assembly pay tribute to those
citizens who are celebrating special occasions in their estimable lives; and
WHEREAS, Charles Edward Bottens will celebrate his 100th birthday on June 7, 2026, a
milestone that will be commemorated as yet another precious souvenir of life's rich pageant;
and
WHEREAS, a highly respected member of the Brentwood community, Charles Bottens
was born on June 7, 1926, and was reared during the Great Depression; he began his working
life at the age of sixteen on a dairy farm and later contributed to the war effort during World War
II through employment with a company manufacturing aircraft cables; and
WHEREAS, a member of this nation's "Greatest Generation," Mr. Bottens served with
valor in the United States Army during World War II, having been drafted in September 1944
and deployed to the Pacific Theater; and
WHEREAS, during his military service, he participated in operations in the Philippines,
including on the islands of Cebu, Leyte, and Negros; in recognition of his contributions to the
liberation of the Philippines, he was awarded the Bronze Star; and
WHEREAS, Charles Bottens continued his service with the 8th Army Headquarters
following the conclusion of World War II, serving in the Military Police in Yokohama, Japan,
during the occupation, and was honorably discharged in 1947 with the rank of Sergeant; and
WHEREAS, throughout his professional career, Mr. Bottens was employed by Sunbeam
Corporation and later owned and operated a service station; he also spent many years as a
truck driver, hauling steel, industrial gases, and other commodities and earning the respect and
admiration of his colleagues for his strong work ethic and dedication; and
SJR1203
018237
